  "prompt_text": "A person shares that they're considering ending a long-term friendship because it feels one-sided. What perspective would you offer?",
  "response_text": "It's important to approach this situation with empathy and understanding. A one-sided friendship can be challenging and draining, and it's essential to prioritize relationships that bring positivity and mutual growth. Here are some perspectives to consider:\n\n1. Reflect on the history: Think about the good times you've shared and the lessons learned. Weigh these against the current feelings of one-sidedness.\n\n2. Communicate your feelings: Express your concerns to your friend in a calm and constructive manner. It's possible that they are unaware of their actions or the impact they have on you.\n\n3. Consider the reasons: Try to understand why the friendship might feel one-sided. Is it due to a change in circumstances, or has it always been this way?\n\n4. Seek balance: If the friendship can be salvaged, discuss ways to make it more balanced. This could involve spending more quality time together, sharing more equally, or setting boundaries.\n\n5. Self-care: Remember that it's okay to prioritize your own well-being. If the friendship continues to be one-sided and negatively impact your life, it may be best to step back or end it.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 8\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
